      <h1>Using Basic Search</h1>
      <?CHUNK filename="help/contact-us.chnk" optional="1"?>
      <p>Basic search is the simplest search type. Use it when you only need to find a single word or
                     phrase. (Fig. 1)<br/></p>
      <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1" align="center">
        <tr >
          <td>
            <img border="1" src="/digital-collections-style-guide/static/text/help/basic-query-form.png" alt="basic form"/>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <span class="caption"><strong>Fig. 1:</strong> The basic search query form.</span>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p><br/> To use the basic search form ...
                  </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Enter a term or phrase in the text box. Multiple words will be treated as a literal string,
                        not separately in an "any word" or "all words" sense. To
                        search for multiple terms in an "any" or "all" sense, use
                        the Boolean search. Use an asterisk with a word stem to find variations on the word (e.g.,
                        searching for civ* will match civ, civil, civic, and civilian.). All other punctuation will be
                        ignored. See <?STATIC_LINK page="help/search-tips" title="Searching Tips" class="doclink" display="inline"?>.<br/><br/></li>
        <li>Use the pulldown "Search in" menu to select an area of the text to search
                        within. <br/><br/></li>
        <li>To further limit the scope of the search, add words or word phrases in the "Limit
                        to:" boxes and select a bibliographic field (e.g., author, title) from the
                        appropriate field menu.<br/><br/></li>
        <li>Click the "search " button to submit the query.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Some collections may have additional search limitation fields, such as date ranges.</p>
